--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Step 1:


**Solve for the area within the region:**

given:
$$y=\dfrac{1}{x\sqrt {4-x^2}},\ \ \text{ interval } \big[1,\sqrt{2}\big]$$

In this case, trigonometric identities can simplify the integral that contains radical expression in the denominator.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Step 2:
**Using Trigonometric Substitution:**
Let $\boldsymbol{\sqrt{4-x^2}}$ as the adjacent side to the angle $\theta$ of a right triangle with opposite side: $\boldsymbol{x}$ and hypotenuse of $\boldsymbol{2}$:
!['slader'](https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/my-test-project-8241d.appspot.com/o/fig3.PNG?alt=media&token=011c9222-d678-408f-8f54-0333bf262583)

Using the figure, the values for the trigonometric functions can be obtained in the following:
$$\begin{array}{c|c}
\begin{aligned}
\sin \theta &=\frac{x}{2}\\
\cos\theta &=\frac{\sqrt{4-x^2}}{2}\\
\tan\theta&=\frac{2}{\sqrt{4-x^2}}\\
\end{aligned}&
\begin{aligned}
\csc\theta&=\frac{2}{x}\\
\sec\theta&=\frac{2}{\sqrt{4-x^2}}\\
\cot\theta &=\frac{\sqrt{4-x^2}}{2}
\end{aligned}
\end{array}$$

So therefore: 
$$\begin{aligned}
x&=2\sin\theta&2\cos\theta=\sqrt{4-x^2}\\
dx&=2\cos\theta \ d\theta
\end{aligned}$$

Substitute the trigonometric functions, so that the resulting Integral can be easily evaluated:
$$\begin{aligned}
y&=\frac{dx}{x\sqrt{4-x^2}}\\[0.8em]
y&=\frac{2\cos\theta \ d\theta}{(2\sin\theta)(2\cos\theta)}\\[0.8em]
y&=\frac{d\theta}{2\sin\theta}\\[0.8em]
y&=\frac{1}{2\sin\theta}\cdot d\theta\\[0.8em]
y&=2\csc\theta \ d\theta\\
\end{aligned}$$



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Step 3:
**Solve the Integral:**

Using the tables of integration, the integral can be shown that:
$$\begin{aligned}
2 \int \csc\theta&=-\ln | \csc\theta + \cot\theta  | +c\\[0.8em]

\end{aligned}$$
Substitute back the values in terms of x:
$$\begin{aligned}
&=-\frac{1}{2}\ln \left|\frac{2}{x}+\frac{\sqrt{4-x^2}}{2}\right|+c\\[0.8em]
\end{aligned}$$
Evaluate the integral, with limits $\big[1,\sqrt{2}\big].$
$$\begin{aligned}
\int_1^{\sqrt{2}}\frac{dx}{x\sqrt{4-x^2}}&=\frac{1}{2} \left[-\ln \left|\frac{2}
{x}+\frac{\sqrt{4-x^2}}{2}\right|\right]_1^{\sqrt{2}}\\[0.8em]

&=\left(-\frac{1}{2}\ln \left|\frac{2}{\sqrt{2}}+\frac{\sqrt{4-2}}{2}\right|\right)-\left(-\frac{1}{2}\ln \left|\frac{2}{1}+\frac{\sqrt{4-1}}{1}\right|\right)\\[0.8em]
&=\left(-\frac{1}{2}\ln|1+\sqrt{2}|\right)-\left(-\frac{1}{2}\ln|2+\sqrt{3}|\right)
\end{aligned}$$





--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Step 4:
**Simplify the solution using Logarithmic Identities:**
$$\begin{aligned}
&=\left(-\frac{1}{2}\ln|1+\sqrt{2}|\right)-\left(-\frac{1}{2}\ln|2+\sqrt{3}|\right)\\[0.8em]
&=-\frac{1}{2}(\ln|1+\sqrt{2}|-\ln|2+\sqrt{3}|)\\[0.8em]
&=-\frac{1}{2} \ln \left|\frac{1+\sqrt{2}}{2+\sqrt{3}}\right|\\[0.8em]
&=-\frac{1}{2} \ln \left(\frac{1+\sqrt{2}}{2+\sqrt{3}}\right)\\
\end{aligned}$$


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Step 5:

Therefore the area is:
$$-\dfrac{1}{2} \ln \left|\dfrac{1+\sqrt{2}}{2+\sqrt{3}}\right|$$


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Result:
$A=-\frac{1}{2} \ln \left|\frac{1+\sqrt{2}}{2+\sqrt{3}}\right|\\$


